# Line endings: LF in the repository and in the working tree, on every
# platform — including Windows, which this project targets.
#
# Windows is the target at *runtime* (the fido provider calls webauthn.dll);
# that says nothing about how the source is stored.  LF is the right choice
# even here, for three reasons:
#
#   1. The Go toolchain is LF-native.  gofmt emits LF on every platform, so a
#      CRLF working tree means every gofmt run rewrites the file and CI's
#      formatting check disagrees with the checkout.
#   2. The trust anchors in roots/ are compiled in with go:embed, so the bytes
#      in the working tree are the bytes in the binary.  A CRLF checkout would
#      embed different bytes than a Linux CI runner does, making the pool's
#      contents platform-dependent.
#   3. The core is meant to build and test on every platform, so an identical
#      checkout everywhere keeps test fixtures byte-stable.
#
# This file is load-bearing: Git for Windows ships core.autocrlf=true in its
# system gitconfig, so without these attributes a Windows clone gets CRLF
# whatever the repo holds.  Attributes override autocrlf and travel with the
# repo, so they apply to every clone and every CI runner.
#
# Git auto-detects binary content; add an explicit `binary` entry below if a
# file is ever misdetected.
* text=auto eol=lf

# cmd.exe resolves goto/call labels unreliably in LF-only batch files.  Batch
# scripts are the one deliberate CRLF exception.
*.bat text eol=crlf
*.cmd text eol=crlf
